
                                                                 Rev. 2
                                                                 
                               MATERIALS
                               =========
                                 
                                 
Introduction:
------------

This is the Darkwind materials doc, so you know what they are
before you start setting them on all your objects.
You can set_material on just about any object on the mud;
specifically, you can set it on those objects which inherit OBJECT.

Additionally, before you are able to use the materials described
below, you must first add the following line at the top of the
object you're creating:

#include <material.h>

Syntax:
-------

The syntax for specifying the material is:

set_material(MATERIAL);

You can mix the material types if you wish.  For example, a ruby-
tipped wand might have this line:

set_material(MAT_WOOD|MAT_GEM);

Material Types:
---------------

MAT_ADAMANTITE  -  is a near-mythical metal highly prized by dwarves,
who are the chief miners of it.  It is a ferrous metal that is somewhat
lighter than steel, but much sturdier.  It is reputed to be nearly
unbreakable, in fact.  Some people claim it is inherently magical, but
this is not the case.

MAT_BONE  -  forms the structural framework of vertebrates.  While fairly
strong, it is also brittle.  Some invertebrates have chitin instead of
true bone, but for our purposes they can be considered the same.

MAT_BRASS  -  is an alloy of copper and zinc.  It is a shiny yellow-orange
color.

MAT_BRONZE  -  is an alloy of copper and tin.  It is yellowish-brown in
color.  It is softer and more malleable than steel, and was once the
primary metal used in weapons and armor.

MAT_CLOTH  -  consists of woven fabrics of natural or man-made fibers.
On Darkwind, they will be almost exclusively natural.  Examples are
cotton, wool, flax.

MAT_COPPER - is a reddish brown metal.  It is fairly common throughout       |
the land of darkwind and because of this is used in many things from         |
cookware to inexpensive jewelry.  Copper is know to be highly conductive     |
of heat and electricity.                                                     |

MAT_CRYSTAL  -  is the name for a material formed by the regular
ordering of molecules into a solid form, such as many of the precious
stones that are mined from the earth (diamond, peridot, ruby).  Also
the name for a very fine, clear glass, typically made with lead.

MAT_ELECTRUM - is a naturally occuring alloy of silver and gold.  It is      |
amber in color.  It is more valuable than silver alone due to its gold       |
content but less valuable than gold.  It is used in many things from fine    |
diningware to jewelry to expensive pieces of armour for kings and nobles.    |

MAT_ENERGY - is used for describing something that is associated with energy |
(such as a ball of lightning) and having no real physical form.  It can also |
be used to describe things such as force barriers and the like.              |

MAT_GEM  -  is what we will call the precious stones, regardless what their
nature.  Certain mineral crystals are highly prized (diamonds, etc),
but there are other noncrystalline gems as well (pearls, amber).

MAT_GLASS  -  is formed from molten sand.  It is easily worked into a
variety of useful and decorative shapes in this state, and cools into a
brittle quasi-crystalline form.  The addition of various impurities
give it color.

MAT_GOLD  -  is a shiny yellow metal that is highly malleable and very
soft.  It is prized for its beauty and rarity, and is used in coinage and
jewelry for this reason.

MAT_IRON - The most common and most useful of metals.  It is usually found   |
naturally in the form of an oxide (such as hematite, magnetite, etc.), or    |
a hydrous oxide (as limonite, turgite, etc.). Iron usually appears dark      |
brown, from oxidation or impurity, but when pure, is a gray or white metal.  |
It is easily oxidized (rusted) by moisture, and is attacked by many          |
corrosive agents.                                                            |

MAT_LEAD - a heavy, pliable, inelastic metal, having a bright, bluish color, |
but easily tarnished. It is both malleable and ductile and has a very low    |
melting point.  It is easily fusible and forms alloys with other metals.     |
It is commonly used to join different pieces of metal or other materials     |
together.  Because of its nature lead is impractical to use alone in weapons |
or armour although some clubs and other bashing type weapons have been know  |
to employ this metal to make the weapon heavier and provide additional       |
smashing power.                                                              |

MAT_LEATHER  -  is made from the cured hides of animals.  When the hide
of large animals, which is generally thicker, is boiled in oil, it can
become stiff and quite durable.

MAT_MAGICAL - this encompasses all other material that may lack a physical   |
form and are not better described as being MAT_ENERGY.  This type may also   |
be used to describe enchanted materials alon with the normal material type.  |                                     |

MAT_MITHRIL  -  is also often called elven steel, or elven silver.  It is
alleged to be the "true" form of silver by the elves, and attributed
nearly magical properties.  Whether or not it is truly magic, it is
known that it is very light for its strength.  A chainmail shirt can be
worn under other clothing without being noticed.  It is also highly
prized by spellcasters, who find that its nature does not prohibit
spellcasting like most other metals.

MAT_NATURAL  -  subsumes all other "natural" substances not herein
described.  A flower would be natural, as would water.

MAT_PAPER - any type of material that is basically boiled, bleached and      |
preseed plants that is allowed to dry and for which is used for writing      |
or other types of craft.  Alchemists use paper in making fireworks and       |
other incendiary devises.                                                    |

MAT_PLATINUM -  One of the rarest of precious metals, platinum also is one   |
of the strongest and heaviest.  It has a rich silvery-white color, is        |
corrosion resistant and is malleable.  It is much rarer than gold and is     |
worth approximately twice that of gold.  Because of its value and            |
decorative nature, it is highly prized for use in jewelry.                   |

MAT_ROCK  -  is any kind of stone.  This technically includes many gems,
but we generally don't set gems to GEM|ROCK.  You might have a
stone club set with gems that would fit that description, though.

MAT_SILVER  -  is a shiny white metal that is lighter than gold but nearly
as soft.  It is usually an order of magnitude less valuable, as well.
Highly decorative, it is used for jewelry and ornamentation as well as
for coinage.

MAT_STEEL  -  is an alloy of iron with carbon, which yields it more
malleable and easier to work as well as less brittle.  Once it was
discovered, it became the metal of choice for making weapons and
armor, replacing bronze.

MAT_STONE - for the most part MAT_STONE is the same as MAT_ROCK.  One may    |
use this for things such as stone tablets or bricks that are not truely      |
rocks.                                                                       |

MAT_TIN  -  is a soft, faintly bluish white metal.  It is quite soft, and is
seldom used by itself but often as an alloying agent with other
metals to form bronze and pewter, among other things.

MAT_WOOD  -  is a hard, fibrous substance that makes up the greater part
of xylemic plants.  It is sturdy and is a good structural agent.  Weight
for weight, it is stronger than steel.  However, wood has many
undesireable properties that make various metals preferable in
many cases.


Additional Comments:
--------------------

Note that the material types must have the "MAT_" in them now as the bits
require it.

